summaries.title: Developing Academic Confidence Through Mentorship
summaries.summaryText: Daniel described feeling initially out of place in rigorous electrical engineering courses, particularly when comparing himself to peers with prior robotics or coding experience. His confidence improved after joining a peer mentoring program where upperclassmen provided guidance and reassurance. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Developing Academic Confidence Through Mentorship
summaries.summaryText: Daniel described feeling initially out of place in rigorous electrical engineering courses, particularly when comparing himself to peers with prior robotics or coding experience. His confidence improved after joining a peer mentoring program where upperclassmen provided guidance and reassurance. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Gender Bias and Collaboration
summaries.summaryText: Priya discussed subtle gender bias in group work but found solidarity in women-in-tech clubs. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Building Community Through Cultural Organizations
summaries.summaryText: Participation in SHPE and campus cultural centers provided Maria a sense of belonging and identity affirmation. These communities offered emotional support and mentorship that she could not easily find in her department. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Balancing Academic Rigor with Limited Peer Representation
summaries.summaryText: Maria described feeling academically capable but often isolated in her computer engineering courses, where few other Latina students were enrolled. She mentioned that faculty were supportive when approached, but that representation and group belonging remained low, especially during first-year lab sections. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Recognizing Privilege and Peer Disparities in Engineering Education
summaries.summaryText: Ethan discussed observing classmates who struggled to access tutoring or networking opportunities. His reflection on his own privilege as a continuing-generation student led him to advocate for more peer tutoring support and accessible design lab hours. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Microaggressions and Invisible Labor in Group Dynamics
summaries.summaryText: Aaliyah recounted repeated experiences of having her technical input questioned in group settings. She also described taking on emotional labor to support other students facing similar bias. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Gender Bias and Collaboration
summaries.summaryText: Priya discussed subtle gender bias in group work but found solidarity in women-in-tech clubs. [Part 3/4]

themes.title: Cultural Representation as a Source of Motivation
themes.description: Seeing Latino professionals at SHPE events reinforced Marias sense of purpose and belonging in a field where representation remains limited. [Extended 2]

themes.title: Peer Mentorship as a Belonging Intervention
themes.description: Daniel emphasized how structured mentorship programs provided psychological safety and belonging cues, normalizing struggle and improving persistence among marginalized students. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Mentorship Networks as Retention Mechanisms
themes.description: Mentorship emerges as a consistent strategy for increasing belonging and persistence for students from marginalized groups. Aaliyahs mentorship program demonstrates how peer-led initiatives can fill institutional gaps. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Acknowledging Structural Advantage and Allyship in STEM
themes.description: Ethans reflections underscore the role of allyship among students who recognize their positional privilege. He highlights how acknowledging systemic inequities can lead to more equitable classroom dynamics. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Navigating Institutional Barriers as a First-Generation Student
themes.description: First-generation identity shapes how Maria interprets bureaucratic and academic systems, creating additional cognitive and emotional labor compared to continuing-generation peers. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Imposter Syndrome Among First-Generation Asian-American Students
themes.description: Daniels experience illustrates how first-generation students often internalize academic challenges as personal shortcomings, especially when they lack peers with shared backgrounds in STEM programs. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Sense of Belonging in STEM for Students of Color
themes.description: Marias reflections highlight how peer representation and visibility in classrooms significantly influence belonging and persistence for Latina women in engineering. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Team Diversity as an Engineering Strength
themes.description: Ethan believes interdisciplinary and culturally diverse teams drive better innovation outcomes, reflecting the growing importance of social awareness in engineering practice. [Extended 4]

themes.description: Aaliyahs experience illustrates how women of color in engineering often balance advocacy roles with academic demands, leading to invisible emotional labor that institutions rarely acknowledge. [Extended 3]

quotes.quoteText: It took me a year to realize struggling is normal  not a sign that Im not supposed to be here. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Daniel describing the turning point after joining peer mentoring programs.

quotes.quoteText: When our robotics team included people from different majors, the solutions got way more creative. It wasnt just engineers thinking like engineers. [Context 3]

quotes.quoteText: I love leading projects, but its exhausting always being the one to explain why diversity matters in engineering teams. [Context 3]

quotes.quoteText: My parents say, Just do your best, but I can tell they really mean, Dont waste this chance we gave you. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Daniel reflecting on implicit cultural pressure from family expectations.

quotes.quoteText: Having mentors who also came from immigrant families helped me feel like my story belonged here too. [Context 3]

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I look around my class and Im the only Latina  it makes me question whether I belong here. [Context 4]

quotes.quoteText: When I walk into a classroom and see no one who looks like me, I remind myself that my presence opens the door for someone else. [Context 4]

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I feel like everyone else just gets it  like Im pretending to belong in these classes. [Context 2]
quotes.context: Daniel discussing his sense of imposter syndrome in engineering coursework.

quotes.quoteText: I realized I had access to engineering summer camps that most of my friends never even heard of  thats when privilege clicked for me. [Context 4]

quotes.quoteText: If I can use my position to make sure everyone gets a fair shot in our projects, thats what good leadership looks like. [Context 2]

quotes.quoteText: I wish there were a clearer path for first-gen students to find mentorship  it feels like everyone else already knows the rules. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Maria discussing gaps in support infrastructure.

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Mentorship for Women in Computing
areasForImprovement.description: Expand mentorship and career guidance for women and first-gen students. [Extended 1]

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Peer Mentoring for First-Generation STEM Students
areasForImprovement.description: Formalize mentoring programs that pair upperclassmen with first-generation students early in their academic journey. These networks reduce imposter syndrome and improve retention rates. [Extended 1]
actionItems: Create opt-in mentoring tracks for first-gen students
Provide mentor training focused on inclusive communication

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Cultural Representation in Engineering Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Students emphasized the importance of seeing role models and mentors from similar cultural backgrounds. Faculty partnerships with student cultural organizations could foster inclusion and belonging. [Extended 1]
actionItems: Integrate cultural competence into departmental events

areasForImprovement.description: Provide stronger academic transition support for first-generation students entering engineering. [Extended 2]

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Visibility of First-Gen Student Resources
areasForImprovement.description: Current communication about financial aid, academic advising, and mentorship resources does not adequately reach first-generation students. actionItems: Add first-gen resource links to department portals
